<ITEM>Buffalo de&s;cribed, vi. 150. Has no name either in Greek or Latin, <HI>ib.</HI> n. Is a native of the warm regions of Africa and the Indies, and was not tran&s;ported into Italy till the &s;eventh century, 152. Mi&s;take of Belon concerning it, <HI>ib.</HI> Refu&s;es to copulate with our common black cattle, 192. Is the dir|tie&s;t of dome&s;tic animals next to the hog, <HI>ib.</HI> The milk of the female buffalo is wor&s;e than that of the cow, but yielded in larger quantity, 193. The &s;kin is of more u&s;e than the fle&s;h, <HI>ib.</HI> Very robu&s;t buffaloes in the kingdoms of Aunau and Tonquin, 195. n. Are very dangerous when attacked and wounded, 196. The &s;ight of the buffaloes at the Cape of Good Hope is bad, 203.</ITEM>
